[3] India (Delhi)
Date: Fri 26 Sep 2008
Source: The Times of India [edited]
<http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/Delhi/Dengue_toll_478_now_600_DBCs_recruited/articleshow/3528857.cms>


With about 2500 domestic breeding checkers (DBCs)
[staff that check on _Aedes_ dengue virus
mosquito vector breeding sites] on strike, MCD
[Municipal Corporation of Delhi] says dengue
cases are on rise in the city. On Thursday [25
Sep 2008], 20 new cases were reported, taking the
toll to 478, including 2 deaths. To make up for
the shortage of DBCs, MCD has decided to engage
600 new DBCs from Friday [26 Sep 2008].

"We don't have the required strength of DBCs, so
we are not able to keep a close watch on
breeding. With these 600 new DBCs joining from
Friday [26 Sep 2008], we will have nearly 2500
DBCs. We are also expecting 200 odd DBCs, who
went on strike, to join work," said Dr NK Yadav,
MHO [municipal health officer], MCD.

According to the MCD officials, the dengue cases
are more than what were reported in the past 3
years. "With 20-25 cases every day, this years'
[2008] dengue situation is quite different. Due
to early monsoon, the breeding season started
early and will continue till November," said a
senior MCD health official.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur A-Lan Banks

