[5] Mexico (Jalisco)
Date: Sat 27 Sep 2008
Source: El Occidental [in Spanish, trans. & summ. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.oem.com.mx/eloccidental/notas/n868613.htm>


After having confirmed the occurrence of 50 new
dengue cases, for a total of 265 infected people
thus far this year [2008], with 4 DHF (dengue
hemorrhagic fever) cases, and with the majority
[of dengue cases] identified in the Guadalajara
metropolitan area, Norma Elizabeth Jacobo
Hernandez, director of Vectors and Zoonoses of
the Jalisco Secretariat of Health, considered
that despite these [cases], these figures are
much lower than those of past years. "There have
been [dengue] outbreaks more important for the
state, such as in Puerto Vallarta. The current
outbreak is not different, except that it is in
the Guadalajara metropolitan area. In 1988 there
were 4508 laboratory confirmed [dengue] cases in
the metropolitan area, the same as in Zapopan,
one of the affected areas," she pointed out.

In addition to this, when there is comparison
with figures from last year [2007], by this same
date in September more than 500 dengue cases had
been identified.

Against this background, Jacobo Hernandez insisted that nothing will
be enough if you do not have social support. "If you look at ... a
neighborhood that is adjacent to one that previously has had [dengue]
cases, [and think] that we are [not] seeing risk ... for us, does not
recognize the fact that the mosquito does not respect [political]
boundaries," she said.

Actions to clean up and spray mosquito breeding
sites will continue, especially in the Zapopan
municipality, which up to today [27 Sep 2008] has
had a total of 185 [dengue virus] infected
patients, of whom 3 had DHF, the most dangerous
form of the disease. "Outbreak control depends on
citizen activity and participation. As for the
Jalisco Secretariat of Health, we will continue
actions to combat the mosquito [virus vector] and
abate the outbreak."

--
