[6] Mexico (Sonora): alert
Date: Wed 24 Sep 2008
Source: Expreso.com [in Spanish, trans. & summ. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.expreso.com.mx/PortalNovo/sitio/nota.php?cod_idioma=3&cod_conteudo=23899&cod=310&tipoINICIO=&codconteudoINICIO=23899>


The Sonora Secretariat of Public Health (SSP)
declared a red alert in the state after the
confirmation of 6 cases of classical dengue in
the municipalities of Benito Juarez, Cajeme, and
Navojoa, due to the rains caused by tropical
storm Lowell, for a cumulative number of 23
affected [people] in the area this year [2008].

In a press conference, the secretary of public
health, Raymundo Lopez Vucovich, assured [the
public] that the "clean patios" strategy would be
reinforced for the "Everyone Against Dengue"
campaign in the region to avoid the spread of the
disease, and issued a call to the community to
help cleaning up their patios and streets of
[water] recipients which could serve as breeding
sites for the mosquito vector, reducing the risk
of [dengue virus] transmission to the populace.

To date, the SSP has confirmed 7 [dengue] cases
in the municipality of Navojoa, 5 in Navojoa
[town], 5 in Guaymas, 3 in Hermosillo,
2 en Benito Juarez, and one more from the
adjacent state of Chihuahua, which requested
medical assistance from Navojoa, for a cumulative
total of 23 [cases] in 2008.

Lopez Vucovich explained that blood samples have
been tested from 450 [individuals], of whom 23
people have been confirmed to have had the
disease, but that 49 [samples] are still under
study, the results of which will be ready on
Tuesday, [30 Sep 2008].

In Mexico, samples from 55 000 febrile [disease
cases] have been tested, of whom 23 000 have
been positive for the vector [sic: virus], with the
states of Guerrero, Veracruz, Oaxaca, and Chiapas
being the most affected.

[Lopez Vucovich] indicated that the SSP promotes
responsible community participation with the
elimination of [water] receptacles, which can
serve as breeding sites for [dengue virus] vector
mosquitoes, and the application of abate in stored
water for human consumption. In case another
epidemic develops, he considers that there will
not be [enough] health or municipal workers
capable of containing it, and because of this he
reiterated his call for citizen co-responsibility
for [preventive] self health care.

--
Communicated by:
HealthMap Alerts via ProMED-mail
